1. Initial Universal Relation
If all attributes from the ER diagram were combined into a single relation, the resulting universal relation would be:
R(
UserID, Email, PhoneNumber, FirstName, LastName, Password, Address,
ReviewID, ReviewText, ReviewDate,
ProductID, ProductName, Description,
OrderItemID, Quantity, UnitPrice,
OrderID, OrderDate, OrderStatus,DeliveryDate
CartItemID, DateAdded, DeliveryDate,
CategoryID, CategoryName, CatDescription,
PaymentID, Amount, PaymentMethod, PaymentStatus, PaymentDate, TransactionID
)
This relation combines attributes belonging to multiple entities such as User, Product, Category, Review, Order, Cart Item, and Payment. Storing all attributes in a single table would lead to:
•	Data redundancy (repeated storage of user and product data)
•	Update anomalies (updating a user's information would require multiple row updates)
•	Insertion anomalies (new products or users cannot be added without unrelated data)
•	Deletion anomalies (deleting a record could remove important information unintentionally)
Therefore, normalization is required to organize the data efficiently and maintain data integrity.

2. Functional Dependencies
User
UserID → FirstName, LastName, Password, Address
UserID →→ Email
UserID →→ PhoneNumber
Product
ProductID → ProductName, Description, CategoryID
Category
CategoryID → CategoryName, CatDescription
Review
ReviewID → ReviewText, ReviewDate, UserID, ProductID
Order
OrderID → OrderDate, OrderStatus, UserID
Order Item
OrderItemID → Quantity, UnitPrice, ProductID, OrderID,DeliveryDate
Cart Item
CartItemID → UserID, ProductID, Quantity, DateAdded
Payment
