These dependencies describe how non-key attributes depend on primary keys.


3. Normalization Process
First Normal Form (1NF)
A relation is in First Normal Form (1NF) if:
    • All attributes contain atomic values
    • There are no repeating groups
    • There are no multivalued attributes
In the universal relation, the attributes Email and PhoneNumber are multivalued because a single user may have multiple email addresses and phone numbers.
To satisfy 1NF, these attributes are separated into their own relations.
Relations in 1NF
USER(UserID, FirstName, LastName, Password, Address)
USER_EMAIL(UserID, Email)
USER_PHONE(UserID, PhoneNumber)
PRODUCT(ProductID, ProductName, Description, CategoryID)
CATEGORY(CategoryID, CategoryName, CatDescription)
REVIEW(ReviewID, ReviewText, ReviewDate, UserID, ProductID)
ORDER(OrderID, OrderDate, OrderStatus, UserID,DeliveryDate)
ORDER_ITEM(OrderItemID, Quantity, UnitPrice, OrderID, ProductID)
CART_ITEM(CartItemID, UserID, ProductID, Quantity, DateAdded)
PAYMENT(PaymentID, Amount, PaymentMethod, PaymentStatus, PaymentDate, TransactionID, OrderID)

Second Normal Form (2NF)
A relation is in Second Normal Form (2NF) if:
    1. It is already in 1NF
    2. All non-key attributes depend on the entire primary key
In this design, each relation uses a single-attribute primary key. Therefore, no partial dependencies exist because every non-key attribute depends entirely on its primary key.
For example:
ProductID → ProductName, Description, CategoryID
Since the key consists of only ProductID, all attributes depend fully on it.
Thus, the relations satisfy 2NF.

Third Normal Form (3NF)
A relation is in Third Normal Form (3NF) if:
    1. It is in 2NF
    2. There are no transitive dependencies
A transitive dependency occurs when a non-key attribute depends on another non-key attribute.
For example, if we stored:
ProductID → CategoryID → CategoryName
then CategoryName would depend on ProductID indirectly.
To eliminate this, category information is placed in a separate CATEGORY relation and referenced in PRODUCT through CategoryID.
This ensures that:
    • Non-key attributes depend only on the primary key
    • Redundant data storage is avoided.
Therefore, all relations satisfy 3NF.

4. Final Relations in Third Normal Form (3NF)
User(UserID, FirstName, LastName, Password, Address)
User_Email(UserID, Email)
User_Phone(UserID, PhoneNumber)
Category(CategoryID, CategoryName, CatDescription)
Product(ProductID, ProductName, Description, CategoryID)
Review(ReviewID, ReviewText, ReviewDate, UserID, ProductID)
Order(OrderID, OrderDate, OrderStatus, UserID,DeliveryDate)
Order_Item(OrderItemID, Quantity, UnitPrice, OrderID, ProductID)
Cart_Item(CartItemID, UserID, ProductID, Quantity, DateAdded)
Payment(PaymentID, Amount, PaymentMethod, PaymentStatus, PaymentDate, TransactionID, OrderID)

Final Justification
The final database design satisfies Third Normal Form (3NF) because:
    • All attributes depend fully on their primary keys
    • There are no partial dependencies
    • There are no transitive dependencies
    • Multivalued attributes such as Email and PhoneNumber were separated into independent relations
    • Entity-specific attributes were organized into their appropriate tables
    • Redundant data storage was minimized, reducing update, insertion, and deletion anomalies
As a result, the schema improves data integrity, consistency, and maintainability.

